The stability of a clock or frequency reference is usually measured by its Allan deviation. The Allan deviation σy(τ), or its square, the Allan-variance, are defined as the variance of the frequency departure yn = 〈δν/ν〉n (where ν is the frequency and δν is its variance during the measurement period) over a measurement period τ: 5.9\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma_y^2(\tau) = {1 \over 2}\left\langle {{{({y_{n + 1}} - {y_n})}^2}} \right\rangle,$$\end{document} where angle brackets indicate averaging.

The S-band communication systems of the DSN that were used for communicating with the Pioneer spacecraft had Allan deviations that are of order σy ∼ 1.3 × 10−12 or less for ∼ 103 s integration times [392]. Using the Pioneer S-band transmission frequency as ν ∼ 2.295 GHz, we obtain 5.10\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
