The velocity change that results from a propulsion maneuver cannot be modeled exactly. Mechanical uncertainties, fuel properties and impurities, valve performance, and other factors all contribute uncertainties. The authors of [27] found that for a typical maneuver, the standard error in the residuals is σ0 ∼ 0.095 mm/s. Given 28 maneuvers during the Pioneer 10 study period of 11.5 years, a mismodeling of this magnitude would contribute an error to the acceleration solution with a magnitude of δaman = σ0/τ = 0.07 × 10−10 m/s2. Assuming a normal distribution around zero with a standard deviation of δaman for each single maneuver, a total of N = 28 maneuvers yields a total error of 5.23\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
